Parliament has not ratified the amendment for the release of Tymosenko
In an amendment to the criminal law, the Ukrainian parliament refused the draft annulment of the paragraph concerning the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected at second reading the proposed amendment aimed at reducing sentences for economic crimes, which could have opened the doors of freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for having concluded an apparently disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgement is not final and the court must rule on the appeal of the sentenced person in December.
Tymosenko described the ruling as a political revenge of the regime and provoked a process of suspicions of partiality of the court also to the west.
The plan to annul paragraph 365 of criminal law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was sentenced, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve.
