The feeding of an obese child: does not have breakfast and takes charcuterie for dinner
More than a third of children aged 9 to 13 have overweight problems, 9% of schoolchildren are above average and 5% are obese.
As current research shows, obese children come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important the environment in which the human being evolves and the models that surround him is.
On the tables of obese children, for example, there are 50 per cent charcuterie more often than in families of children with normal weight.
19% of obese people had fries at dinner according to the survey conducted with an awareness campaign "Obesity is not a coincidence"
In the families of fat kids, sport is also not a habit, which is now the case of most schoolchildren today - only 15% replied that at least once a week parents found time for active movement.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place during the last school year and involved 900 pupils from primary schools in Czech Republic.
It was the second edition of "Obesity is not a coincidence", action supported by the General Health Insurance and the Unilever company.
Since the beginning, more than 12,000 students from sixth to third have enrolled in this project.
One of the determining factors that causes a dramatic increase in the number of overweight or obese children is the lack of proper nutrition and not enough exercise.
"Only half of the children questioned indicate for example eating 5 times a day breakfast-in case - lunch - snack-dinner, which is a basic principle of a good diet", indicates one of the results of the survey.
Without breakfast and cold meats at dinner
Specialists draw attention to the fact that a healthy development requires some basic details such as a family breakfast at the same time.
In the Czech Republic, only 23% of students' families eat at the same time.
In most families each has breakfast alone.
And the worst thing that's been noted is that one tenth of the population doesn't have breakfast at all.
Breakfast, however, is the basis for a good daily diet.
The questionnaire showed that the families of obese children consume unhealthy fries more often.
Almost every student - not to mention weight - drinks sweet drinks every day (70%).
More than 40% of the children questioned do sports regularly but for parents this is half, only 15%.
Get ready for your diet
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to prepare their own diet from the possibilities offered according to their own taste and personal opinion.
"The preferences of Czech children aged 12 to 15 are far from ideal in terms of healthy eating".
Among their favorite dishes are lots of cakes, meats and sweets.
"The most alarming is in particular a high preference for sweet lemonade", is indicated in the survey results.
For lunch, pasta took the first place right in front of white meat.
Children did not want starch at all and the preference for fish and vegetable meals was very low.
Focus on health
The survey also showed that children are ready to change their habits once they receive ad hoc information.
"During a review of a group of survey participants who had completed the questionnaire after the awareness-raising session "Obesity is not a coincidence", there was a determined desire to move towards a healthy diet", the results of the survey were reported.
The most striking was, for example, in the case of sweet lemonade, as children began to give preference to drinking water.
Children most often checked on the questionnaire white meat and fish as the main dish and would reduce sweet dishes and "knedliky" (Czech speciality of bread flour pellets or potatoes).
