History of IBM: From cheese slices to flights in the cosmos.
IBM (International Business Machines) was born in New York a hundred years ago and initially had the complicated name Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was named IBM in 1924 - originally a brand used by a branch of a firm in Canada and South America.
The basis of the future IBM was the merger of four firms whose history is linked to the 1980s of the nineteenth century.
They had technologies such as the old "pointers", pendulums that recorded the arrival and departure of employees.
The architect of the new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 chaired the company's Supervisory Board.
Flint hired the head of a competing firm, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The leader then cast a shadow on the founder of the firm - Watson's ideas have been the foundation of society's identity and culture to date.
Watson headed the firm in 1952.
IBM, as his name says, began with the production of all possible machines for business and commerce - from cheese and meat slicers to cash registers.
During Watson's first four years of leadership, sales increased to $9 million and began to expand in all parts of the world.
Watson was so irreplaceable to the firm that after 40 years of management, his son occupied the director's chair, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his direction IBM began the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM's people and computers helped NASA guide the flights in the cosmos - on Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the flight on the Moon.
In 1964 IBM developed the first family of computers - the IBM System/360.
The classic PC that determined the computer standard of the time with the name IBM 5150 came on the market in 1981.
Twenty years later IBM sold its computer factory to the Chinese company Lenovo, but bought the company of Consulting Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to take care of consulting and services with high added value.
The strategy that has succeeded IBM over the last three years - is the Smarter Planet concept "a smarter planet".
Its objective is the intelligent use of technology in areas not yet exploited, such as transport and city management.
With regard to the field of commerce IBM has recently developed a platform "Smarter Commerce" that helps trade to manage the whole business cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in our territory.
She founded her branch in Czechoslovakia in 1932, then the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, in addition to IBM RT, there is also Brno's strategic outsourcing centre.
The Central for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and there is also the research and development team at the global level that deals with speech recognition.
