After this summer's tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how can we find them?
Easy... Connect to Facebook.
"We realized it wasn't that difficult to find them," says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by the DEMOS think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is full of so much personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site's advertising tool to find the people they are looking for with scientific precision - the way the mercatists have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. It targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to answer a survey. The questions asked concerned their level of education, their attitudes to violence and their optimism about their own future.
By getting in touch with these people via Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
"This is a new way of doing research," says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not surprising at all: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young people and against immigration.
But surprisingly, "those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who stay behind their computer screen."
DEMOS's study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new essential tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all the topics that affect health issues such as social trends, thanks to the "Like", wall publications and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the "data supernova" generates an explosion in research, increasing the number of research works whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook is that it allows you to study people you could not approach on the street.
"Before, when you were trying to investigate people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them."
"You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you in," says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say that the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social problems.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who spoke on Facebook about their intoxicated exploits were far more likely to be alcoholics than discreet students.
Megan Moreno suggested that student colleagues, such as counsellors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
"You can't deal with a problem if you don't diagnose it," Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children's Health, Behaviour and Development at the Seattle Research Institute for Children, says the Washington Post.
"We know how to identify children at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized."
Facebook also has constant access to the information of its users.
The data team at the site studied statistics on the romantic situation and Valentine's Day, the turnout in the 2010 mid-term elections and an index of national happiness (thanks to the information only available - the champions of digital freedom have for a long time maintained that the site could make available its data treasure to others for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not - in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of kilometres away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of an investigation that they haven't even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, it is quite different online.
"I don't think many users have ever thought about the fact that a researcher can study their profile," says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As long as they knew, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user's wall.
"What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things," says Neil Selwyn.
That's why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and a pen remain the best tools we can use.
"Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people," he says.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and social is not in front of a computer."
