Lies have destroyed quarries and convulsed countries.
Congressman Anthony Weiner, a celebrity of the Internet, was an idiot by quickly issuing denials contradicted by irrefutable evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards was charged with violations of campaign funding related to the coverage of an extramarital liaison.
And then, none of the people who lived the story will ever forget the media circus that President Bill Clinton started by lying during his second term about his sexual involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
The stories of cheating in school and university tests are legion.
There have been cases where teachers have given the test answers to students in order to get a good look at their performance evaluations.
Mentors who should teach the contrary send the message that lies and cheating are acceptable.
How much deception do we encounter?
On a given day, studies show that you can hear 10 to 200 lies.
In fact, many of these are pious lies.
Another study showed that foreigners lie three times in the first 10 minutes of their meeting.
Detecting or spotting lies is an essential skill that everyone must acquire, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a social game similar to, say, charades, where the goal is to exclaim: "I've had you", the detection of deception is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades in prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research into such projects, notably in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the oldest myths about lying have been demystified.
The liars look you in the eye.
They do not stutter, blush or not always wave.
Do not conclude that liars are difficult to detect and difficult to expose.
A qualified lie detector can discover the truth by examining the structure of the statement, facial micro-expressions, question formation and response time.
I have spent several years examining scientific results in the vast body and always emerging from knowledge about deception, and it is clear that the detection of deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and useful for navigating our complex world - especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviews, negotiation or management.
Good liars are able to read the others well, making them comfortable, managing their own emotions and intuitively detecting how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men say more lies "centered on them" while women say more lies "centered on others" - usually to protect someone's feelings - that married people lie less often to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell tend to be huge).
We also know that if you are perceived as an unbeliever, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How can you tell if someone's lying?
First, observe the normal behavior of your subject.
That's what we call "establishing benchmark data."
This helps to provide a reference point for measuring future changes.
Observe the posture of your subject, the laughter, the vocal quality.
You need to know if someone normally moves his feet constantly so as not to make unfair accusations when you see him moving his feet in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for clues of verbal and non-verbal misleading behaviour.
Consider these clues red flags, not evidence of deception.
Deceiving people can immobilize the upper body when they try to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean towards an exit, change posture significantly or present a relief of "post-interview" - an exaggerated sigh of relief, a change of posture when all the difficult questions have passed.
Interrogators often falsely indicate that the interview is completed just to try to trigger the post-interview reaction.
Also, pay attention to the vocabulary of your subject.
The well-known Scott Peterson skirmished using the past while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, triggering a national search to find her.
Misleading individuals can also use a distanced language: "I have not had sex with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or repeat entirely a difficult question.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "wooden language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... if I remember well... to my knowledge."
This makes the response perceptive rather than factual and is often a red flag.
There is no magic formula for the detection of lies, but the development of skills to recognize deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone avoiding victimization by scammers in their professional and personal lives.
