Climate adversity has curbed the economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa unemployment and informality increased, foreign investment declined and the economy contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-called change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climatic adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase does not occur, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing trillion losses for the agricultural sector, limited the potential of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction in economic activity in general by 3.6 per cent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historical decline of 31.16 per cent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the Jelly Allocation Report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 per cent suffered total damage and the remainder of 21.07 per cent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, maize and chickpeas.
The decline in economic activity led, until November, to a steady increase in unemployment in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment in the State during the first three quarters of the year was accelerated, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloans were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 per cent of the economically active population, in the second quarter the rate became 5.28 per cent and from July to September the average continued to rise to 6.19 per cent, a rate which represents more than 74 thousand Sinaloans unemployed, an increase compared to the first half of 18 thousand 969 people.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to economist Gerardo López Cervantes, Director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly according to the actions carried out by public policy.
"What we see is an increase in unemployment which is due to various factors, among which the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who make dollars illegally it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and to use them in something," he says.
Detained migration
López Cervantes reported that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
"The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been limited, firstly because of entry difficulties and secondly because by entering they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which means that unemployment is rising," he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the Sinaloan labour market is getting worse by considering the high level of lack of seriousness which predominates between working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 per cent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker at any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason of lag for the state are the low wages, the entity has the lower wages of the Country, according to the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Forecast.
The average monthly earnings of Sinaloan workers until September were 5 thousand 352 pesos, well below the national average of 7 thousand 375 pesos.
Contravention of FDI
Apart from the decrease of the economic activity and the increase of the unemployment, in 2011 the largest reduction of the Direct Foreign Investment of the last 10 years has been recorded, according to the Secretariat of Economy from January to June the State FDI has reached 630 thousand 697 dollars, which represents a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 dollars recorded in the same period of the previous year.
In turn, the Economic Development Secretariat of the Government of the State records a total investment of 17,280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the service sector.
Debt
In view of the economic contraction scenario, the Government of the State requested in July at the public congress the approval of a credit of 3 trillion pesos for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the objective of reviving the economy, the approval of the State congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no debt benefit was observed in any sector of the State economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the employer sector, Mario López Valdés' first year of government demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo López, President of the National Chamber of Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonisation of the wishes of the different sectors, including the Government of the State.
"The performance of Sinaloa's economy during this year has been really very poor, we have to work hard to recover the land we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, we have had to align the effort of all and above all the good already synchronized march of this new government team, hope that next year is much better," he said.
Economic slowness
Loredo López said that events like the frosts at the beginning of the year held the state economy back and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the result of several events, between which the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close much below the expectations we had," he says.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers' Confederation of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa has declared that the State is to be channeled towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe it is necessary to develop a long-term programme that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the state, because it is important that we detonate all the potential of Sinaloa's material and human resources," he says.
A lot to do
The President of the Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that better channel the efforts of the Government.
"In general terms, I would say that the Government has made efforts to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances, but it is important to develop a long-term program," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown advances in the way public policy is managed.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the Government is more inclusive, what I can say is that we have worked a lot and the Government is aware that there is still a lot to do," he says.
