The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to introduce the new government that will face a crisis that has put this country on the brink of economic disaster
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the whole Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with President Giorgio Napolitano to confirm that he can form the Government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in his majority by technocrats, even if it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his conversations with the political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," said the former European Commissioner for Journalists.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The "frame is now well drawn," he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than usual, while Italy fought a political and financial crisis that pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former European Commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Underlining the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of the Italian bonds BTP at 10 years above the 7 percent, the level in which Greece and Ireland had to be saved.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of the Italian employer Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much".
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's potential for success was greatly stimulated by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told the press.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed Monti's technocrat majority government.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what is likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could lead to a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by observing that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
Monti began consultations on Monday with political parties, trade unions and employers' groups and youth and women's organizations.
He'll finish his meeting tour Tuesday through the night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who empowered an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels between uncertainty about the success of the new Prime Minister.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for Eurozone's current financial defences.
Monti said his Government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement the reforms before advancing the elections.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist that it must be formed only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that mutual mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
