""Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become reality"
In the exclusive interview with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam said the band is ready to offer one of its best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They have waited more than 20 years, but the group assures that for them it will also be a dream come true to happen in this country.
It is that bassist and founding member Jeff Ament assured, speaking exclusively with Viva, from Brazil, last week.
The group is in the South American wing of its tour celebrating two decades of work and Sunday 20 will make its only stopover in Central America.
On that day they will arrive at the National Stadium, starting at 7:30 p.m., next to the Los Angeles The X group and the Las Robertas Nationals.
This is an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcription of which can be found in La Nación on the Internet.
For his Costa Rican followers, the fact that Pearl Jam will happen in Costa Rica is a dream come true. Are you aware of what your fans are experiencing?
Going to Costa Rica is a dream that has become a reality for us too.
This is our second time in South and Central America and so far it has been grandiose.
I spent only one vacation in Costa Rica; it is such a beautiful country and I think we can spend a few days there.
So we are moved to carry our music there.
I ask you, because there is a kind of devotion to the band, fans live intensely the previous days.
What is your message to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying with us for all these years.
It took 21 years for us to arrive in Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry that so much time had to pass until this concert.
Some people already say his concert is the biggest show of the year.
Does this add a little pressure to your visit.
Some of the larger shows that we have offered in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We have offered two gigantic shows in Sao Paolo and we hope that it has put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We are really looking forward to it.
We love this country, we like surfing and the jungle; for both things, Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you discover Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
We have a lot of surfer friends and I have a very good friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves are amazing there.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, next to Mexico, are great places to surf; that's how we learned, through the people who love surfing.
When you see the tour, you offer huge shows, with lots of songs.
What did you plan for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never been there, we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to do the best possible show, with a wide variety of songs; we will try to perform two songs from each album and offer our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the directory.
What is that supposed to mean?
I think it's partly because we have nine records and we can perform more than 120 songs and each one likes different songs, which is why it's very difficult to choose which songs to perform each evening.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven't played in a very long time, it helps us stay focused and surprises us because it reminds us of the reasons why we love these songs and that we may have forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting to us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting to people.
With this tour, you celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you've done?
Yes, absolutely.
First of all, I don't think either of us had imagined that we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we did it for more than 20 years makes it seem like a dream.
We continue to tell our blessings and the fact that we can continue to make music together is very exciting to us.
We love each other and love to create music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of the grunge?
It has always been an honour for us to form part of this group of major groups.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement emerges from a group of friends and is unusual.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups come out of the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honour for us to be part of the Seattle band.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we took part in a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we're lucky to be friends with all of them again and it's an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came up.
It is also very strange that a group like yours keeps itself united and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
First, I believe that we are all lucky to be alive and, second, we are all concerned about others.
We are all intimate friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give freedom to everyone to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other's music and that could not be better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity has not been easy; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
