Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official procession, headed by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and composed of various ministers and bosses, will launch this Tuesday a visit to Mexico to expand trade between the two nations and address political themes of the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of a long agenda of meetings with political and commercial authorities and a meeting with the community of Uruguayan residents in Mexico, according to the agenda circulated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents in the city of Guadalajara, will be "propice for the exchange of information in political affairs between the two nations", according to information published by the Presidency of the South American country on its web page.
According to local media, Mujica is trying to convince Calderón to support Uruguay in the incident with France that took place when the French representative, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country on the list of tax havens, in the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community countries that continue to be tax havens, a declaration that led to the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultations by his ambassador from that European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group made up of the world's strongest emerging and developed countries, and has, since January this year, been in force with the South American country to exchange tax information to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to speed up the implementation of tax exchange agreements to get out of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) 'grey list', integrated by countries that do not implement all international standards of tax co-operation.
On the trade front, Mexico and Uruguay have had a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in force since 2004, which has increased the exchange of goods between the two nations.
The moustachu plumber moves to three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario struggled, tirelessly, for 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the wicked Bowser, but he had never done it in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the love of the young one in stereoscopic technology.
