Japan is reborn after the earthquake
GDP rose 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ended the downward spiral of early March
Since March, Japan's economy has been paralysed, recovering from the devastating earthquake that has become a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe in Japan since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government calculated the material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, seems to have eased.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the Gross Domestic Product data between July and September were used to permanently turn the page: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% in annualized rates.
That recorded in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - assumes, in addition, the greatest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
Part of the recovery is due to the resumption of equipment acquisitions to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the post-tsunami.
In fact, the companies have increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the decrease of 0.9% of capital expenditure observed from January to March, the first decrease after six months of uninterrupted increase.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - the infrastructures, to use the deficiencies to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly due to changes in domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable increased by 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
The stigma of the yen
Tokyo returned to the internal market when the yen - the Japanese currency - became one of the "refugia values" elected by investors fleeing the debt crisis in the Eurozone and the forecast turmoil of the United States, a privilege that weighs like a slab in the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger division, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose economic float line is determined by the health of major technological groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, were responsible for their low results between July and September for the yen's contribution.
While the markets continue to have their headquarters in the peripheral EU countries, Yoshihiko Noda's government does not drop the guard.
"We must monitor the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of the floods in Thailand and the rapid appreciation of the yen," said Motohisa Furukawa, Secretary of State for Economic Policy yesterday.
And indeed, the prospects are not at all encouraging.
The Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) mentioned that the majority of member countries presented clearer signals of economic slowdown in September.
The indicator that anticipates the inflection points of the world economy has highlighted that the main powers are being held back.
Because it has dropped four decimal places to 100.4 points, compared to 100.8 in August.
Eurozone was even below the average, which is in level 100, n lowering eight decimal places to 99.13 points.
Athens Feeds Back Doubts
Papadimos says the adjustments will be approved, but the Conservatives will not sign any written commitment
With the peripheral risk premiums triggered and the uncertainty resettled in the parks, Greece continues to be entangled in the maze that leads to the end of the major European debt crisis.
The feeling that the "consensus" of the new transitional government in Hell is imposed rather by the demands of Brussels than by a real conviction of the political forces is beginning to be confirmed by the facts.
While the new Prime Minister, Lukas Papadimos, reported yesterday that there is no alternative for structural reforms and that the period of one hundred days established in his designation may be short to implement them, the leader of the conservative New Democracy party, Antonis Samaras, assured that he would not support the new austerity measures in any case and reiterated his demand for new elections for the date planned, that of 19 February.
"The main task of this government is to implement the decisions of the summit of 26 October," Papadimos said when he opened yesterday a parliamentary debate that will end tomorrow with a vote of confidence for the new Executive.
A package of 24 programmes to boost employment, reform of the civil servants' disciplinary code and new measures against tax evasion will be the first initiatives.
However, Samaras No's message casts doubt on his position: "We have committed ourselves to helping the Transitional Government, but we have committed ourselves to nothing more."
The conservative leader has gone a step further in his pulse than EU and IMF, the agencies that must release the 8,000 million that Athens urgently needs, and has made it clear that he will not approve any letter of commitment to implement the adjustments.
But the European Commission, still irritated by the impact caused by the va-tout of the Papandreu referendum, reiterated yesterday that its demand is firm: it will only release the aid if the new government and the leaders of the main Hellen parties do not sign "a written commitment without ambiguity as soon as possible".
The spokesman for Economic Affairs, Amadeu Altafaj, explained that the troika inspectors would return "very quickly" to Athens to discuss with the new government "the elements necessary to pay the sixth instalment" of 8,000 million, even if there is no definitive date either.
Greeks still have a lot to do.
Queen Sofía: "These are instruments for progress and hope"
The Queen emphasises the "preponderant" position of Spain with regard to this type of finance
Spain "has reached a preponderant place at world level in the role of Microfinances".
Queen Sofía recalled that in the last two decades the country has become the world's second largest donor in terms of this instrument of cooperation, the essence of which lies in the fact that it is an "instrument for social progress, justice and hope in a better future for all humanity, based on trust in the human being".
The Queen inaugurated yesterday the Fifth World Microcredit Summit in Valladolid with the certainty that "there is no doubt" that this type of operation is "absolutely indispensable" to achieve the Millennium Goals set by the United Nations for 2015, and, "very especially, in that which aims to reduce to half the volume of people living on incomes under one dollar a day, to which is set the "threshold of poverty".
Spain "continues to work" to expand the network of beneficiaries "in every corner of the world, and takes on this task with "responsibility", said Queen Sofía, who hoped that the initiatives and the original contributions during the Summit, which will last until Thursday, "guarantee the creation of new capacities and better opportunities for the poorest and especially for women", the main beneficiaries of these loans.
We have "achieved many goals" and "we face many challenges".
The Microcredit Summit is seen not only as a forum for debate, but also as the platform from which to push "two basic goals".
Thus, Her Majesty explained that the goal is that by the end of 2015 there are 175 million poor families who have accessed these financial services and that one hundred million of these families are going beyond the poverty line in which they now live.
The impulse in the conception of microcredits in Spain and the rest of the world "followed the path initiated a few years ago in a pioneering way" by Muhammad Yunus, stressed Queen Sofía as an "act of justice and due recognition".
And she described the father of this instrument as an "admirable idealist in the universal cause of the fight against poverty", the work she has known for 15 years, when the Queen travelled to Bangladesh to know on the ground her lending policy.
This experience was followed a year later by the first World Summit in Washington and other meetings such as those celebrated in Côte d'Ivoire in 1999, Canada in 2006, and "at each meeting I was able to see a continuous evolution", explained Her Majesty, whose relationship with this project brought him yesterday the qualifier of "head of family" gathered in Valladolid from the "banker of the poor".
Finally, Queen Sofía ended her speech by encouraging those present to participate in the debate and in the search for solutions to move forward in the fight against poverty.
"Etiquetic imperative"
Foreign Minister Trinidad Jiménez warned that solidarity "is an ethical imperative" for any democratic state.
In this sense, she explained that it would be a mistake to vinculate cooperation with developing countries at times of economic prosperity, as it is a "permanent obligation".
Jiménez considered that microcredits presuppose "a serious and rigorous policy dedicated to the eradication of poverty", and now "more than ever" the governments of developed countries must work under criteria of solidarity and not let it be the victim of cuts.
For Spain, microcredit is "one of the main lines of development cooperation".
The Secretary of State for International Cooperation, Soraya Rodriguez, applauded "the success" of giving "trust" to "excluded people to whom all close the door"; and the mayor of Valladolid, Francisco Javier León de la Riva, welcomed people present in a city that "opens its doors contaminated with the spirit of solidarity".
The CDU proposes to elect the European President by universal suffrage
The first day of the Congress of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU), on Monday 14 November in Leipzig, took place without any real difficulties for Angela Merkel, Chancellor but also President of the Christian Democratic Party.
The future of Europe was not originally planned for in the programme but was imposed in the autumn, especially to satisfy the activists who consider the government's policy too lax vis-à-vis the Greeks today and perhaps the Italians tomorrow.
The motion on the Presidency of the European Commission, proposed by the management, was adopted almost unanimously.
Out of 1001 delegates, only nine voted against and ten abstained.
The standing ovation of several minutes to which Angela Merkel and then, a few hours later, Wolfgang Schäuble, the very Europhile Minister of Finance, were entitled, at the end of their speeches, did not leave room for doubt.
The mastery of the Chancellor's idea - and of the motion - is based on a slogan: the answer to the crisis "is not less Europe but more Europe".
Not only because Europe is peace, but because "nine million jobs depend directly on the euro".
For the Chancellor, "the time has come for a breakthrough in Europe".
This could lead to amendments to the Treaty of Lisbon to strengthen the control of the European Union over the fiscal policies of the euro area countries, but it could also lead to the election of the President of the European Commission by universal suffrage "in order to give a face to Europe".
This is, in any case, one of the proposals of the motion adopted by the Congress, the inspiration of which is clearly Wolfgang Schäuble.
Of course, it is unlikely that the Twenty-Sevens will agree quickly on this revolution: Britain is hostile to it and the leaders of the CDU believe they know that Nicolas Sarkozy is also hostile.
But the milestone is set.
Similarly, the delegates overwhelmingly rejected the proposal to weigh the weight of each country in the Executive Board of the European Central Bank according to the weight of each economy, which obviously amounted to strengthening the weight of Germany.
In an effort to calm the climate within her party, the Chancellor multiplied references to Konrad Adenauer and Helmut Kohl, but she also did not seek to win her congress on the back of the "small" European countries or countries in difficulty who were quick to criticize the arrogant Germany.
While the motion on Europe devotes a paragraph to the importance of "French-German friendship", Angela Merkel did not mention France.
Except in hollows.
Remembering that two centuries ago, Leipzig had been at the heart of a bloody battle.
In fact, it was one of the most humiliating defeats of the Napoleonic army.
What does sickness arrest fraud mean?
After the allowances, the UMP and the government launched the offensive on sick stoppages.
Nicolas Sarkozy will be in Bordeaux on Tuesday 15 November to visit a family allowance fund, and deliver a speech on the theme - recurring since 2007 - of the fight against social fraud and assistance.
And to accompany this offensive, which starts from a desire to make savings in a context of rigour, but is no less announcing an axis of the presidential campaign to the right, the majority wants to focus on sick stops.
First of all, with a view to saving the budget: the government plans to impose a fourth day of default on employees in the private sector before taking over a stoppage of work.
Clearly, without a specific company agreement, an employee who falls ill would lose four days' pay, i.e. at least 15% of his monthly income.
A measure that could provoke anger, but which would yield 280 million euros, according to Les Echos.
And that would be accompanied by another measure, more symbolic in scope: to impose on civil servants a day of non-compensated deficiency in the event of a stoppage of work (they have so far no waiting period, compared to three days in the private sector).
While these issues are under discussion, the majority are also reviving the issue of fraud, this time targeting abuses linked to work stoppages.
"The controls will be much more important and, if you are taken, you will pay back," warned Xavier Bertrand at RTL's microphone on Sunday, November 13.
As in other cases, the publicity effects seem somewhat disproportionate to the reality of work stoppage fraud.
This has been the subject of constant monitoring and political offensives since 2002, most of which have borne fruit.
The French are no more ill than elsewhere in Europe.
Let us first look at the national figures.
According to the National Health Insurance Fund (CNAM), more than €237 million of daily allowances were issued in 2006.
According to the Institute for Research and Documentation in Health Economics, daily allowances in 2008 accounted for 5% of health expenditure, with 11.3 billion euros.
Of this amount, 46% concerned maternity leave and accidents at work, and 54% concerned sick leave, i.e. EUR 6.2 billion.
And so 2.5% of health spending.
In 2010, the French had an average of 14.5 days off work, compared to 17.8 days in 2009, according to a study by Alma Consulting.
An average that hides some discrepancies: another survey, published in 2007 by the career management website Monster.com, showed that 75% of the 40,000 French employees interviewed said they had taken no sick days.
Another study, this time from Health Insurance , states that in 2010, 37% of sick leave was for less than 8 days, 22% from 8 to 14 days, 15% from 15 days to one month, 15% from one to three months and 11% beyond.
When compared with their European neighbours, French employees are no more likely than elsewhere to stop working.
A long study conducted in 2010 by two CNRS researchers showed that between 1994 and 2001, the overall absence rate (for health reasons or not) in France varied between 10% and 11%, compared with 20% and 28% in Denmark, 15% in the United Kingdom or 16% and 18% in the Netherlands.
Fraud on sick leave represents very little in the face of undeclared work.
As far as fraud is concerned, it is only a small scale.
The strengthening of legislation since 2002 means that checks are systematic on sick stoppages of more than 45 days.
In 2008, out of 1.5 million inspections, CNAM found that 13% of the 285,000 short-term stops were "unjustified or too long", or 37,050 cases.
In the case of detentions of more than 45 days, systematically checked, 11% of 1.2 million, or 132 000, were "unsuitable or unjustified".
In total, 169,000 "unjustified" cases out of several million employees who have had a sickness stoppage.
A figure which represents very little in comparison, for example, to that of work in the dark.
According to UMP MEP Dominique Tian, author of a report on the issue in June, it would amount to 9 to 15 billion euros of tax loss per year, which is more than the total cost of daily allowances, and thus infinitely more than fraud against them.
Papadémos: Greece to implement new adjustment plan
Greece will need a new adjustment programme to restore its economy.
That is what Prime Minister Lucas Papadémos said to Parliament on Monday 14 November, adding that the 100 days given to his unity government would not be enough to accomplish this task.
"In order to continue efforts to restore the economy, we need the support of our European partners and a new budgetary adjustment programme," said the Head of Government, who delivered his first public speech at the opening of the debate on the vote of confidence in Parliament on Wednesday.
The implementation of the decisions taken at the euro area summit on 27 October will be the "main task" of the new government, as the country's participation in the euro area "is at stake", he added.
As a result, Mr Papadémos predicted that the country's public deficit would be reduced "to around 9%" of GDP by the end of the year, after having been 10.6% in 2010 and 15.7% in 2009.
The Right Rejects New Austerity Measures
Antonis Samaras, the leader of the right, on Monday supported the measures already approved to try to get out of the debt crisis but warned that his party would not commit to additional austerity.
"We will not vote in favour of new measures," he said at a meeting with the deputies of his party, New Democracy.
He agreed with the objectives of reducing the deficit and the debt, and of combating waste, but opposed to any policy that would prevent economic recovery.
To Olli Rehn, the European Commissioner for Economic and Monetary Affairs, who warned that the IMF and the EU would not release the necessary EUR 8 billion loan without written guarantees from all parties that they would support the planned measures, Antonio Samaras replied that his word was enough and that he would not sign anything under external pressure.
It is necessary to legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide, says a committee of experts
Canadians live in denial of death, according to the Royal Society of Canada report
With respect to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Canadian society lives in the denial of death.
Only 9% of Canadians agree to talk to their doctor about the conditions in which they want to die and make arrangements for that.
This is one of the findings of an impressive report by the Royal Society of Canada, which involved six experts in a variety of fields, including ethics, law and medicine.
This committee recommends that the government amend the Criminal Code to allow assisted suicide and euthanasia, where appropriate, with a patient deemed competent to make such a decision.
At the outset, the experts cite a recent survey by the Economist Intelligence Unit, which compared the quality of death in 40 countries around the world.
While Canada ranked 10th, the study notes that "the medicalization of death in Canada has created a culture in which people are afraid to address the subject of death."
Medicalization or not, 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, report the experts commissioned by the Royal Society of Canada.
And despite the desire of most Canadians to die at home, 68.6% of them end up dying in hospital.
Across the country, Quebec has the highest rate, with 86% of deaths occurring in hospitals.
On the sensitive issue of euthanasia and assisted suicide, the authors of the report come to conclusions that run counter to the position of the federal government, which has already said that it does not want to change anything in the Criminal Code regarding euthanasia and assisted suicide.
According to the experts, who have also reviewed all countries where these approaches are legalized or decriminalized, there is no evidence that this decriminalization leads to abuse in application, i.e. the practice of euthanasia or assisted suicide on non-competent or non-consensual persons.
On the contrary, Jocelyn Downie, co-signatory of the report, said yesterday in a teleconference, there would be more cases of these outbursts precisely in countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are not legalized.
"Euthanasia is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal."
"Assisted suicide is practised in Canada, where it is clearly illegal," explains Jocelyn Downie.
Canadians in Support of Euthanasia
Recall that 85% of Canadians have already voted in favour of euthanasia because they believe it would allow people at the end of their lives to alleviate their suffering, according to a 2010 Angus Reid poll.
And 66% believe that legalizing euthanasia will not have the effect of sending the message that the lives of the elderly or disabled are less valuable.
As for those involved in assisted suicide, respondents estimate that 41% should not be prosecuted.
When it comes to maintaining or ceasing care with a patient, the situation is less clear, say the authors of the report.
Therefore, in the list of their recommendations, they suggest that it be stated in the Criminal Code that the withdrawal of care for which there has been a legally valid refusal is not criminal.
The Expert Panel also calls for health professionals to be trained in the duty to respect a refusal of end-of-life care, without fear of criminal prosecution.
With respect to palliative care, the committee calls for governments, health care institutions, and physicians to work together to ensure better palliative care beyond cancer.
Finally, with respect to palliative or terminal sedation, which is already widely used in Canadian health institutions, the committee asks that it be considered, when it is not used to reduce physical pain, such as euthanasia, and that it be subject to the same procedures.
Reservations by other experts
Some experts in the field of health law have already expressed reservations about the findings of the Royal Society of Canada Expert Report.
Pierre Deschamps, a specialist in health law, described the position of the experts who signed the report as "extreme", among other things because it does not limit the practice of euthanasia to the terminally ill.
"This opens the door to a situation where anyone who is tired of life and who is over 18 years old could ask for help to commit suicide," said Deschamps, who had consulted yesterday a summary of the report.
Mr. Deschamps also points out that the authors of the report seem to place the individual's autonomy above all other values that participate in the social fabric of society.
"In society," he says, "there are beacons and constraints."
Health law expert Margaret Somerville also expressed "strong opposition" to the report's findings, which she described as "pro-euthanasia demonstration".
Margaret Somerville, who is herself a member of the Royal Society of Canada, is particularly challenging the report's data on the absence of abuse in some countries where euthanasia and assisted suicide are legalized, in the Netherlands and Oregon.
King of Jordan calls on President Assad to leave power
Damascus denounces a "complot"
Syria is increasingly isolated
Supporters of Bashar al-Assad demonstrated yesterday in front of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs.
Diplomatic pressure intensified yesterday on Bashar al-Assad's Syria, which, with Russia's support, resists them and denounces a "complot" against the country.
Two days after the Arab League suspended Syria, the European Union stepped up its sanctions against Damascus, while Turkey and Jordan, neighbouring Syria, took a stand in favour of President Assad's departure.
King Abdullah II of Jordan yesterday was the first Arab leader to call on President Bashar al-Assad to "leave power" in Syria, where some 40 civilians and members of the regime's forces were still killed.
"If Bashar had the interest of his country at heart, he should resign, but he should also create the conditions for a new phase of Syrian political life," said the king of Jordan, a neighbouring country of Syria, in an interview with the BBC.
For his part, the head of Turkish diplomacy, Ahmet Davutoglu, deplored the failure of the Turkish mediation efforts undertaken since the beginning of the year with the Syrian regime.
"Those who are not at peace in the Middle East with their peoples and cannot satisfy them will leave," he said, referring to Syria, a neighbouring country towards which Turkey is taking an increasingly tough line.
For its part, the United States welcomed a "strengthening of consensus against Assad and the actions of the Syrian regime", following the decisions of the Arab League and the European Union.
"The international community, the United States, the EU, the Arab League, countries like Turkey are taking an increasingly harsh tone" in the face of repression in Syria, noted Mark Toner, a spokesman for the State Department.
Meanwhile, 16 civilians and at least 19 members of the regime's forces perished in the Dar'a region of southern Syria, announced the Syrian Observatory for Human Rights (OSDH).
Two other civilians perished "on exchanges of fire and shelling with heavy machine guns in Jobar" in the besieged city of Homs, according to this NGO.
At a press conference, Syrian Foreign Minister Walid Mouallem said that the country was "directing towards the end of the crisis".
He also reacted strongly to the Arab League's decision to suspend Damascus from its work, which he said constituted a "dangerous step".
Syria "will not bow," he added, assuring that "conspiracies against Syria will fail."
After its decision to suspend Syria, the Arab League is now studying a "mechanism for the protection of civilians" and wishes to send 500 members of Arab human rights organizations, media and military observers to the country.
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppé also expressed his support for sending UN observers to help protect civilians from the repression of the regime, which he believes is locked in the "paranoia".
A new extraordinary meeting of the League is scheduled tomorrow in Rabat to take stock of the implementation of the plan to end the crisis decided on 2 November, including the withdrawal of armed forces from the cities in dispute and the release of the arrested demonstrators.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov yesterday found the decision of the Arab League "uncorrect", while China urged Syria to implement the plan to end the crisis, while refraining from supporting any sanctions against Damascus.
Italy
Monti demands time from the markets and sacrifices from the Italians
The future head of the Italian government, Mario Monti, demanded a little time from the markets to form his team and implement a program, which will contain "sacrifices", in order to regain the credibility lost in the last months of the Berlusconi government.
The former European Commissioner was in discussion with the political parties yesterday before meeting the trade unions and employers today.
It should set up a relatively small cabinet composed of technocrats outside Parliament.
"Monti spoke of an important programme with great sacrifices," said Francesco Nucara, a member of one of the many small parliamentary groups involved in the talks, after meeting the President-designate.
The Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, said he expected Mario Monti to seek a vote of confidence in Parliament by Friday to ensure that the new government has sufficient support.
The consultations will conclude with the presentation by Mr Monti of a short list, probably of a dozen ministers, to the Head of State, Giorgio Napolitano.
Mr Monti commented on the nervousness of stock and bond markets yesterday, asking them for time.
In "democracy, there are specific deadlines" to prepare a government and its program, he stressed, saying "somewhat markets will be patient and understand".
Its appointment by the President was initially welcomed by the markets, but the concern has taken over in particular after an unexpected fall in industrial production in the euro area in September.
The Prime Minister-designate should set up a team with mainly technocrats, although he stressed that he would like to include "policies".
The new government is expected to last until 2013, the date of the next legislation, he said.
According to the Speaker of the Chamber of Deputies, Gianfranco Fini, the new government will gain the confidence of Parliament by Friday.
Mr Monti undertook, once he had taken office, to work urgently and with the aim of "re-establishing Italy as a protagonist" in Europe.
A spokesman for Commissioner Olli Rehn stressed that "even with a new government, our diagnosis of the Italian economy does not change".
The EU, convinced that Rome will not achieve its objective of a balanced budget in 2013, despite the austerity plans adopted in recent months, called for further austerity measures.
The Italian "patron of bosses" Emma Marcegaglia, who will see it on Tuesday, also insisted on the need to revive the economy, "because a country that has no growth cannot respect the parameters of deficit".
Mr Monti, renowned for his competence and independence as European Commissioner (1994-2004), represents a "period change" for Italy after 17 years of "berlusconism", the "teacher" symbolising "the challenge of seriousness" and "another Italy", according to editorialists.
The great unknown will be the longevity of his team.
President Napolitano would like to avoid early elections, as Italy must place 200 billion euros in state bonds by April 2012.
Russian scientist helped Iran's nuclear programme
A Russian scientist, Vycheslav Danilenko, helped Iran develop a nuclear-weapon-usable detonator, said an American nuclear-risk NGO on Monday.
The Institute for International Science and Security (ISIS) draws on the recent report of the International Atomic Security Agency (IAEA) and other documents from that United Nations agency to identify this researcher.
Last week the IAEA expressed its "serious concerns" about a "possibly military dimension" of Iran's nuclear programme.
According to ISIS, drawing heavily on IAEA documents, Mr. Danilenko, born in 1934, worked for three decades from the 1960s in a Soviet military nuclear centre in Chelyabinsk, Urals, and was allegedly involved in the manufacture of synthetic diamonds by explosion.
In 1989 or 1991, he reportedly left the centre to establish a company producing "nano-diamonds" in Kiev.
His company's economic difficulties would have led him to contact the Iranian Embassy in Ukraine in 1995.
He then allegedly cooperated with the Iranian programme from 1996 to 2002, before his return to Russia.
In its latest report, the IAEA refers to "strong indications that Iran's development of a nuclear detonation system" was assisted by the work of a foreign expert, who was not only familiar with this technique, but who, as a Member State informed the Agency, worked for most of his career on this technology in the military nuclear programme of his country of origin".
Anti-Muslim crimes and offences increased by 50%
Crimes and crimes against Muslims increased by almost 50% from 2009 to 2010, while at the same time, other racial and religious violence decreased slightly or little, according to FBI statistics released Monday.
According to these figures, the total number of violence against Muslims increased from 107 in 2009 to 160 in 2010, or 49%, compared to a 13% increase in violence against Catholics, a 4% decrease in crimes against Jews and an overall 14% increase in anti-religious crimes and offences.
The total number of "hate crimes" increased very slightly to 6,628 cases, of which 47.3% were motivated by racial differences and 20% by religious differences, according to the FBI.
"After a decline in 2009, it is disturbing to see these crimes and crimes rise again," stressed the human rights organisation Human rights First, "the increase in anti-Muslim violence is particularly significant," the organisation added in a statement.
"Human Rights First has long stressed that violence against Muslims, as well as all forms of hate crimes, must be seen as a serious violation of human rights," adds Paul Legendre, head of the organization.
"The U.S. government can and must do more to address these abuses," he added, believing that this could be achieved through improved police reporting on "hate crimes."
The "hate crime" in U.S. federal law is a legacy of the time of the civil rights struggle.
This legislation was passed after the death of Martin Luther King to punish violence related to race, skin colour, religion, origin and now sexual belonging.
Twitter changes its platform and looks more like Facebook
The Twitter micro-blogging site introduced changes on Monday in the presentation of its platform, in particular to allow its users to observe the activity of those they follow, which makes its service a little more like that of Facebook.
A new "activity" tab and another "name" allow you to follow more legibly, live the activity of the other "Twittos", the users whose messages are followed ("tweets") and those who follow you.
This allows you to know if they are forwarding messages, subscribing to new accounts, having favorite messages, etc.
This new Twitter format was tested "on a small percentage of users in August" before being broadcast to the entire network on Monday, told AFP Twitter spokesperson Carolyn Penner.
Twitter, which was known for its somewhat instinctive functioning, with somewhat esoteric terms (RT to redifuse a message from someone else, #followfriday to recommend to follow another user) making the insiders happy, thus opens up to a wider audience with a handling more comparable to that of Facebook and Google+ mainstream networks.
On the network, users were discussing the relevance of this innovation with the use of "tweets".
"It's useless, invasive, and it looks too much like Facebook," writes @jemb123.
"The Activity feature will help me better track some elements of my Twitter feed," sent @dannykronstrom.
Austria
inclusion of a budgetary "golden rule" in the constitution
On Tuesday, the government of the major ruling Social Democratic/Christian Democrat coalition in Austria decided to include in the constitution a budget "golden rule" in order to reduce public deficits and thus avoid a possible degradation by rating agencies of Austria's sovereign rating (triple A).
It was the Social Democratic Chancellor Werner Faymann who himself announced this decision at the end of a Council of Ministers, while the Austrian public debt was 74.6%, well above the 60% maximum laid down by the Maastricht Treaty, but well below the debts of countries such as Italy, Greece or Spain.
"If Austria's solvency were reduced by only one notch, from AAA to AA+, we would have to pay three billion euros in additional interest each year," argued Vice Chancellor and Christian Democrat Foreign Minister Michael Spindelegger.
Austria is thus following up on a request from the Brussels summit of the euro area member countries on 26 October last: the Heads of State and Government had then called for the inclusion by the end of 2012 of the reduction of public deficits and a return to the balance of public accounts in the constitution or in a law of the same value.
The system adopted by the Austrian Government is closer to the "German model", since Germany was the first European country to adopt such a "rule".
By 2017, the structural government deficit will have to fall by 0.75% of gross domestic product (GDP) each year and, as of 2017, the federal government's structural government deficit will not have to exceed 0.35% of GDP each year, while regional states and municipalities will have to present balanced budgets.
The objective is to bring public debt up to 2020/21 under the 60% criterion set by the Maastricht Treaty.
Yen strong
Noda threatens new intervention in the foreign exchange market
Japanese Prime Minister Yoshihiko Noda warned on Tuesday that Japanese authorities would again intervene in the foreign exchange market should the yen continue to rise.
"We will intervene as we did last time if we see excessive volatility" in the yen exchange rate, Mr.Noda explained to the Senate.
On Tuesday, the Yen went up not far from the historical levels that prompted the Japanese authorities to intervene on 31 October.
On that day, Tokyo massively sold yen for dollars in order to lower the value of the Japanese currency, which had just set a new record of strength since 1945 against the green note.
But the yen has been steadily rising since then, boosted by purchases from investors who consider it a "refugee value" in these uncertain times of global economic slowdown and debt crisis in Europe.
The dollar went back Tuesday under the 77 yen and the euro fell below the symbolic 105 yen bar, close to the levels that triggered the last intervention.
Prior to the 2008-2009 financial crisis, the dollar was around 120 yen and the euro over 160 yen.
This surge in the Japanese currency is affecting exports to Japan as it increases the cost of Made in Japan products and reduces the value of foreign income by Japanese firms when they convert them into national currency.
"Japan is struggling to rebuild itself" since the earthquake and tsunami of 11 March that devastated the Tohoku region (northeast), stressed Mr Noda who fears that this increase in the yen will kill the fragile recovery in the bud.
The third world economic power returned to growth in the third quarter -1.5% compared to the previous quarter - for the first time in a year, thanks to a rebound in exports and consumption of households led by the disaster.
But the Prime Minister considered that the high price of the yen did not reflect "the economic fundamentals of Japan".
Finance Minister Jun Azumi, for his part, called on the Bank of Japan (BoJ), which opened a two-day meeting of its Monetary Policy Council on Tuesday, to take all possible measures to weaken the yen.
But the deputy governor of the institution, Hirohide Yamaguchi, warned that the BoJ had already taken "appropriate measures", suggesting that no further monetary easing was to be expected on Wednesday.
At its last meeting at the end of October, the issuing institute increased its purchases of Treasury bills by 5,000 billion yen (€47 billion), raising the ceiling on the amount it spends on purchases of various financial securities to 55,000 billion yen (€519 billion) to flood the liquidity market.
