Energy policy:
facts must prevail over dogmas
If there is one subject which cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity have a direct impact on the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is healthy that an election should be an opportunity to reflect on such issues and on the place nuclear power holds.
The debate will be fruitful only if it explores all the economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic change will lead to a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge part of the world's population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to compensate for the scarcity of fossil resources in order to continue to produce electricity permanently, not to mention the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in order to combat climate change, a subject that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case for Belgium, which is subjecting its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor for Switzerland, which just intends to build only last generation power plants.
On the other hand, the Czech Republic, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their projects with determination.
The United States, on the other hand, decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their fleet by resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
While the German model, which focuses on renewable energy, is sometimes presented as an example, reality upsets the discourse.
Berlin's choice will result in higher electricity prices, increased energy dependence and increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a surge in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal-fired power plants.
Within a few months, all these unfortunate effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be considered.
Europe's wind champion, from which he derives 30% of his electricity, he is also one of the biggest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; by virtue of which his CO2 emissions and the price of his electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the other hand, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill than that of French households.
While in a globalised economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction on the part of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the fine declarations on the reindustrialisation of our country and the defence of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not object in principle to this energy, the polls show.
Recall that our country's energy policy has made it possible to build an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Highly export-oriented, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets and makes them very creative of non-localizable jobs.
If France were to decide to leave nuclear power, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing the annual 6 billion euros of French exports of nuclear equipment and services as a source of grief.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no miracle source of electricity generation, nor is there any evil.
The development by Areva of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a Safety Authority which exercises intransigent and transparent control over existing power plants as well as the Flamanville yard.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession of safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, operated under normal operating conditions, with no human or environmental consequences.
At Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the tragedy.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident resulted from two natural disasters of unprecedented magnitude that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did for the previous two.
As a result of this approach and of cooperation between the safety authorities, the operators and the French and German manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians who want to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by giving them the free way to seize the leadership in the inevitable development of nuclear.
It is essential and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to allow emotion, dogma and partisan maneuvers to dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy pursued under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of the number, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "countries of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has come to light, with the Minister of the Interior (read Libération of 23 May) proclaiming that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant servers".
But it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
There is a fairly broad consensus on this subject between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was set by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country with nearly 2 million migrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, the fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared to the left as well as to the right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be given to immigrants.
In his programme, François Hollande confines himself to trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may be paid for electorally; but it is economically very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth, wages and employment in countries receiving immigrants.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and harming employment.
Concerns about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they are likely to replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
However, experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly engaged in trades in sectors in need of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national wage earners, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors in which training does not follow the job supply.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will find it difficult to work in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants make the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri has thus calculated that a 1% increase in migration flows leads to an increase between 0.6 and 0.9% in real long-term wages.
And this does not take into account the fact that the diversity provided by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organisation estimates, for example, that in Germany, an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue less expenditure) of EUR 150000 to public budgets on average over the whole of his life.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of the mandate, to look for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, as a deterrent to immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
Europe has invented democracy, European democracy remains to be thought of
Democracy is a precious asset; it is also a fragile asset.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the goulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would be enough for democracy to triumph over its enemies definitively, to vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, from Napoleon "le Petit", that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression" as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, education, Enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis in Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is just as much, and first and foremost, a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum has in this respect had the value of double revealing: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought of in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have now moved, and that, for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer shooting in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized on the basis of necessity and in dispersed order.
A blank-seing with the absolute European monarch or a joint jump in the void of nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but we want a common exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level, of full right, serene and continuous.
There are no crises in Greece, Italy, Spain and Portugal - there is no point in stopping the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that bends to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, which suffers from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated on the international stage.
There is concern about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
For it is together that Europeans can reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The end of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After a long time of fighting this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone today calls for the European economic government.
All right.
But to think of it without stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "do" republicans.
The Revolution in interest could not be enough.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be done by building a more democratic Europe politically, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
Contactless smart cards are becoming more widespread
The global smart card show opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in an optimistic climate.
The year 2011 is expected to end with an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank card, SIM phone...), to more than 6 billion units, according to Eurosmart.
The most important segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or pay for your purchases by simply approaching the card of a reader.
This year, 460 million contactless smart cards are expected to be sold worldwide, compared to 320 million a year earlier!
Their share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million expected units) and to represent almost 10% of the global smart card market (6,925 million cards).
Long behind the Asia-Pacific region, Europe is gaining ground for contactless payment.
Some 26 million Visa credit cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But the big surfaces put double bites.
Carrefour has issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards this year.
To move up the speed, banks must now equip their customers.
"Two major French establishments have committed themselves to systematically distributing to their customers bank cards equipped for contactless customers in the future," said Gérard Nébouy, General Manager of Visa Europe France.
Banks test mobile payment
But this is only a first step towards the means of payment of the future: the mobile phone.
Few devices are now equipped with the NFC (Near Field Communication) technology needed to perform transactions.
"They're late."
"But they should finally see a real boom next year."
"We are counting on selling 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012," explains Marc Bertin, president of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
The Agricultural Credit announced yesterday the launch of a test from December to June in Caen.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and collaborators will be equipped with a contactless payment case.
BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale, too, said yesterday preparing for the placing on the market of an offer allowing its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
From Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front spreads
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
The long-sustained links between the al-Qaida terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are being confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's Deputy Minister for Foreign Affairs, Abdelkader Messahel, even said that Algiers has now "acquired certainty".
"The way in which the two organisations operate and the reports from the intelligence services show that there is good cooperation," he explained without further clarification.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the abduction of two Frenchmen in Niger last January reportedly uncovered bridges.
Kidnapped in a Niamey restaurant by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day along with several of their kidnappers during an operation launched by the French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerian investigators had to find several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist axis
The analysis of past calls refers to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues are of particular interest to the investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who spent a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram and the other to a man who claims to be close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but we probably have to wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"It has been known for years that the sect enjoys external financial and intellectual support and that it is becoming more and more active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months these "supports" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and discourse of Boko Haram or in his modus operandi, which now involve the use of increasingly complex suicide bombers or explosive devices and on the same bill as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore put pressure on Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as a community of uninteresting illuminants.
Rapid success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist iman Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in haoussa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in northern Muslim Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is experiencing rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for sharia law while its activists engage in the fight against the ungodly central government.
The latter are aimed primarily at churches, bars and administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, increasing attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, without nuances.
The army's taking over the city, 800 people are dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, was killed in prison.
From then on the sect will radicalize and leave its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, she claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos and another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the secure police headquarters during a suicide attack, his first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria is now a matter of concern to all security professionals.
While Aqmi has invested Mali and Niger, as Somalis in al-Shebab operate in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, in a meeting in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was "ready to share all the information."
