Nord Stream, a new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, directly linking Western Europe and Russia through the Baltic Sea, has entered into service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, this new pipeline that links Russia directly, under the sea, to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have together turned the wheel of the valve commanding the entry of Russian gas into the West European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first tube of 1,224 km connecting the St Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second tube is due to be completed by the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas, equivalent to all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site looks like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The Nord Stream will make it possible to deliver gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close it access to West European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream with a "new German-Soviet pact", with reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is to say whether the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of supply.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, since the project created a breach between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia has been able, in just five years, to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich western countries, which are heavily gas-consuming, and whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically," François Fillon confirmed by inaugurating this pipeline, demonstrating how political and economic the major gas contracts are.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by Gazprom's leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of gas arrival.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of concrete-coated steel to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to the Second World War.
"A hundred had to be removed or destroyed, as a precaution," said Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
There has also been a need to increase measures to protect fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel Towers, which nothing interrupts over its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A monitoring platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project officials abandoned it while the Swedes were reluctant to see a Russian state corporation permanently established off their coasts.
"In case of damage, we stop the passage of gas in less than a minute," says Jens Müller.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the pipeline escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds to leak every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the condition of the pipeline is carried out by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for outdoor observation, as well as by an aircraft circulating inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter in diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, he provides precise information on possible metal deformations.
The pipeline was designed to operate for 50 years without any repairs.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, who keeps 51% of the shares.
They were joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire gas transmission capacity to the company for 20 renewable years.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported," says Jens Müller.
Financing for the construction of the gas pipeline was provided by shareholders at 30% and by bank loans at 70%.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to pay their own costs, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic at Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the coming gas before it is transferred to the German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskin, a brand book.
Created some fifteen years ago by an Italian company, Moleskin wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventures, hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine book is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a off-white color, as aged by time.
However, the Moleskin notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a design but distinguished notebook.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is based on an old production technique, the mole skin (smack skin) which refers to a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
"Moleskin has restored to the taste of the day an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the head of the brand at Modo Modo.
Success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces.
We are far from the confidential production of the first years, where only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskin crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to draw up a sketch of the buyer, because the notebook seduces both the businessman and the student and the professionals.
Like Moleskin, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultivated.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, has almost 100 today and has two offices since 2008; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from La Fnac to small downtown shops and has been able to impose her identity.
"We followed the air of time and this new need for writing, despite the rise of e-mails," explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched an exhibition "Detour" where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, agendas, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a range of supports.
A success that made envious: in autumn 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in Moleskin's history.
Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of the disabled opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Disrupting?
"No," said Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
"The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable. "
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, much remains to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before entering employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years of age (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a university degree and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, all these criteria make it particularly difficult to return to employment and are "the crux of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, Managing Director of Tremplin, an association set up in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
That's for the objective brakes.
Still the unspoken, the mentalities that are changing, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed had "a low level of knowledge of disability", with "over-representation of people in wheelchairs, mental or intellectual disabilities".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the target of 6% employment of disabled workers set out in a law of 1987.
The latest available figures, which date from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, Managing Director of the Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of "taxed" establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, increasing from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also reflects a real awareness, especially in large groups."
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
